[Problem Analysis]
1. Problem Essence & Type:  
   We have an \(n\times n\) grid with values \(a_{i,j}=(j-1)\,n + i\).  From the bottom‐left \((1,1)\) to the top‐right \((n,n)\) you must take exactly \(2n-2\) moves (each either up or right), and the sum of the visited cells (including start and end) must equal \(k\).  This is a combinatorial “monotone grid path” problem with a twist on path weights.

2. Algorithm Choice & Rationale:  
   - Compute the minimum possible sum (`min_sum`) when you go all the way up first, then all the way right.  
   - Observe that swapping an adjacent “Up→Right” pair (`UR`) into `RU` increases the path‐sum by exactly \((n-1)\).  
   - The total number of such inversions that can be eliminated from the “all-Up then all-Right” ordering is \((n-1)^2\), so the maximum sum is `min_sum + (n-1)^3`.  
   - Hence the attainable sums form an arithmetic progression  
       min_sum, min_sum + (n-1), min_sum + 2*(n-1), …, max_sum.  
   - Check if \(k\) lies in the interval \([\text{min\_sum},\text{max\_sum}]\) and \((k - \text{min\_sum})\bmod (n-1)=0\).

3. Complexity Analysis:  
   - Time per test case: \(O(1)\) (just a few integer arithmetic checks).  
   - Total time: \(O(t)\), where \(t\le100\).  
   - Space: \(O(1)\).

4. Edge Cases & Pitfalls:  
   - Use 128‐bit (`__int128`) for intermediate products (e.g.\ \(n^3\)) to avoid overflow.  
   - Ensure \(n\ge2\) as per constraints.

[Code Implementation]
```cpp
/* 
  Problem C: PolarBear's Path Sum
  Key technique: 
    - Compute min sum (all Ups then all Rights),
    - each UR→RU swap raises sum by (n-1),
    - max swaps = (n-1)^2 ⇒ max_sum = min_sum + (n-1)^3.
    - Check k in [min_sum, max_sum] and congruent mod (n-1).
*/
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
using int64 = long long;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int T;
    cin >> T;
    while(T--){
        int64 n, k;
        cin >> n >> k;
        // Compute min_sum = n*(n^2 + 2n - 1)/2
        // Compute max_sum = min_sum + (n-1)^3
        __int128 N = n;
        __int128 min_sum = N*(N*N + 2*N - 1) / 2;
        __int128 delta = (N-1)*(N-1)*(N-1);
        __int128 max_sum = min_sum + delta;
        __int128 K = k;

        bool ok = false;
        if (K >= min_sum && K <= max_sum) {
            // Check (K - min_sum) % (n-1) == 0
            int64 mod = n - 1;
            // We can reduce (K - min_sum) mod mod safely in 128-bit:
            __int128 diff = K - min_sum;
            if ((diff % mod) == 0) ok = true;
        }
        cout << (ok ? "YES\n" : "NO\n");
    }
    return 0;
}
