[Problem Analysis]
1. Problem Essence & Type  
   - We have a 5×N grid. There are M pea‐shooters and K torchwoods placed at distinct cells. A pea‐shooter in row x at column ys fires beans to the right at speed 1 cell/s; a bean’s base damage increases by 1 per second of flight (=distance traveled). Each torchwood in the same row at column yt that the bean “passes through” adds +2 to that bean’s damage.  
   - We receive Q independent queries: a “bungee zombie” appears at row x, column y; we must compute the total damage it immediately receives from all beans that arrive exactly at that cell (i.e., beans shot earlier that have traveled distance y–ys).  
   - This reduces to, for each query (x,y), summing over all shooters in row x with ys<y:
       Damage contribution = (y−ys) + 2·(# of torches in row x with columns in [ys+1, y]).  
   - We must answer Q up to 1e5 queries, with N up to 1e6, M,K up to 1e5.

2. Algorithm Choice & Rationale  
   - Preprocess separately per row (1..5):  
     • Sort shooter columns S_x and build prefix sums of positions.  
     • Sort torch columns T_x.  
     • For each shooter at position s_i, compute P_i = (# torches ≤ s_i) via binary‐search, then build prefix sums of these P_i.  
   - For a query (x,y):  
     Let p = #shooters in row x with ys<y = lower_bound(S_x, y)−S_x.begin()  
     Part1 = Σ_{i=1..p} (y − s_i) = p·y − Σ s_i  
     Let tc = #torches in row x with col ≤ y = upper_bound(T_x, y)  
     Part2 = 2·Σ_{i=1..p} (tc − P_i) = 2·(p·tc − Σ P_i)  
     Answer = (Part1 + Part2) mod MOD.  
   - Each query costs O(log M + log K). Preprocessing costs O((M+K)log(M+K)).  

3. Complexity Analysis  
   - Time: O((M+K)·log(M+K) + Q·(log M + log K)) ≲ 1e5·17 + 1e5·34 ≃ 5e6 ops.  
   - Space: O(M+K+Q).  

4. Edge Cases & Pitfalls  
   - Rows with zero shooters or zero torches (must handle p=0 or tc=0).  
   - Large N but only M/K positions matter; we never build O(N) arrays.  
   - Beware negative intermediate mod results—add MOD before final mod.  

