   Algorithm: Precompute per-row shooter positions and torch counts, with prefix sums.
   Query in O(log M + log K) using binary searches.
*/
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;
using ll = long long;
const int MAXR = 5;
const ll MOD = 998244353;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n, m, k, q;
    cin >> n >> m >> k >> q;
    // For rows 1..5, store shooter columns and torch columns
    vector<ll> shooters[MAXR+1], torches[MAXR+1];
    for(int i = 0; i < m; i++){
        int x, y;
        cin >> x >> y;
        shooters[x].push_back(y);
    }
    for(int i = 0; i < k; i++){
        int x, y;
        cin >> x >> y;
        torches[x].push_back(y);
    }
    // Precompute per-row sorted lists and prefix sums
    // prefS[r][i] = sum of the first i shooter columns in row r (1-based)
    // prefP[r][i] = sum of (#torches ≤ shooterCol) over the first i shooters
    vector<ll> prefS[MAXR+1], prefP[MAXR+1];
    for(int r = 1; r <= MAXR; r++){
        auto &S = shooters[r];
        auto &T = torches[r];
        sort(S.begin(), S.end());
        sort(T.begin(), T.end());
        int sz = (int)S.size();
        prefS[r].assign(sz+1, 0);
        prefP[r].assign(sz+1, 0);
        // Build prefix sum of shooter positions
        for(int i = 1; i <= sz; i++){
            prefS[r][i] = (prefS[r][i-1] + S[i-1]) % MOD;
        }
        // Build prefix sum of #torches ≤ S[i-1]
        ll accP = 0;
        for(int i = 1; i <= sz; i++){
            // count torches ≤ S[i-1]
            int cntT = int(upper_bound(T.begin(), T.end(), S[i-1]) - T.begin());
            accP = (accP + cntT) % MOD;
            prefP[r][i] = accP;
        }
    }

    // Answer queries
    while(q--){
        int x, y;
        cin >> x >> y;
        auto &S = shooters[x];
        auto &T = torches[x];
        auto &PS = prefS[x];
        auto &PP = prefP[x];
        // p = # shooters with col < y
        int p = int(lower_bound(S.begin(), S.end(), y) - S.begin());
        if(p == 0){
            cout << 0 << "\n";
            continue;
        }
        // Part1 = p*y - sum_{i=1..p} S[i-1]
        ll sumS = PS[p];  // modded
        ll part1 = ((ll)p * y % MOD - sumS + MOD) % MOD;
        // tc = # torches with col ≤ y
        ll tc = upper_bound(T.begin(), T.end(), y) - T.begin();
        // Part2 = 2 * (p*tc - sum_{i=1..p} P_i)
        ll sumP = PP[p];  // modded
        ll part2 = (( (ll)p * tc % MOD - sumP + MOD ) % MOD) * 2 % MOD;
        ll ans = (part1 + part2) % MOD;
        cout << ans << "\n";
    }
    return 0;
}
```

**Explanation of Key Steps**  
- We reduce each bean’s damage formula to two accumulable sums per shooter:  
  (1) flight‐distance damage = (y−ys), and (2) torch boosts = 2·(count of torches in the path).  
- Both sums are linear in simple prefix sums if we sort the shooter positions and precompute, per shooter, how many torches lie to its left.  
- At query time, binary searches yield the counts in O(logN).

[Problem Analysis]
1. Problem Essence & Type  
   We start with two positive real numbers  
     X = √(a/b),   Y = √(1/c),  
   where 0 < X,Y ≤ 1.  We are allowed up to 2·b applications of the three functions { arcsin, arccos, tan }, each application counting as one operation.  We need to decide if X can be turned exactly into Y in at most 2b operations.  

   A key trigonometric‐algebraic fact is:
     •  arcsin(√(p/q)) → θ,  then tan θ = √(p/(q–p)),
     •  arccos(√(p/q)) → θ,  then tan θ = √((q–p)/p).  
   Hence in exactly 2 operations you can transform the pair (p,q)  
     → (p, q–p)   or   → (q–p, p),  
   provided 0 < p ≤ q.  Interpreting p/q ↦ X² and aiming for 1/c, one checks that “reaching” Y=√(1/c) is equivalent to walking in integer pairs from (a,b) to (1,c) via repeated “subtract smaller from larger” steps (and optional swap)—essentially the subtraction‐based Euclidean algorithm.  

   Since each two‐operation block reduces max(p,q), one sees that in ≤b such blocks (≤2b operations) we can reach any intermediate pair whose max‐coordinate is < b.  Moreover:
     – If at any point p=1 and q=c (or swapped), we're done.
     – 1 can only show up if gcd(a,b)=1.
     – If a·c = b then √(a/b) = √(1/c) already and 0 operations suffice.  

   Therefore the answer is “YES” exactly when  
     (i)  a·c == b   (instant equality),  
     OR  
     (ii) gcd(a,b)==1  AND  c < b.  

2. Algorithm Choice & Rationale  
   A direct check in O(log N) per test for gcd(a,b) plus the simple products/comparisons above covers all cases.  

3. Complexity Analysis  
   – Time: O(T · log max(a,b)) for up to 10³ test cases—plenty fast.  
   – Space: O(1) extra.  

4. Edge Cases & Pitfalls  
   – Exact equality when a·c == b: 0 ops needed.  
   – Must require c < b for gcd(a,b)=1 branch; c=b only works if equality.  
   – If gcd(a,b)>1 and not an exact equality, one can never reach p=1.  

[Code Implementation]
```cpp
/* 
   Problem F: “压轴の数学题”
   Key idea: Each 2‐operation block simulates (p,q)->(p,q-p) or (q-p,p).
   We can reach (1,c) in ≤b blocks iff either 
     a*c == b  (X==Y from start), 
   or gcd(a,b)==1 and c < b.
*/
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int T;
    cin >> T;
    while(T--){
        long long a, b, c;
        cin >> a >> b >> c;
        // Case 1: already equal => 0 operations
        if (a * c == b) {
            cout << "YES\n";
            continue;
        }
        // Otherwise we need to see if we can reach p=1, q=c by subtraction‐based Euclid
        if (c < b && std::gcd(a, b) == 1) {
            cout << "YES\n";
        } else {
            cout << "NO\n";
        }
    }
    return 0;
}
```

[Problem Analysis]
1. Problem Essence & Type  
   - We start with \(X = \sqrt{\tfrac{a}{b}}\) and want to reach \(Y=\sqrt{\tfrac1c}\) by repeatedly applying the three functions \(\arcsin(\cdot)\), \(\arccos(\cdot)\), and \(\tan(\cdot)\).  
   - Key observation: the only way to stay in \([0,1]\) after two operations is to pair an “arc” with “tan,” and these two‐step moves exactly implement the Euclidean‐subtraction step on the pair \((p,q)\) representing \(\sqrt{p/q}\).  
   - Concretely, from \(\sqrt{p/q}\) with \(0<p<q\):
     - If \(q-p>p\), then \(\tan(\arcsin(\sqrt{p/q}))=\sqrt{p/(q-p)}\).  
     - If \(p>q-p\), then \(\tan(\arccos(\sqrt{p/q}))=\sqrt{(q-p)/p}\).  
   - Thus each 2-op step replaces \((p,q)\) by \((\min\{p,q-p\},\max\{p,q-p\})\) — exactly the subtraction step of the Euclidean algorithm.  
   - We repeat until we either reach \(\sqrt{1/c}\) (i.e.\ pair \((1,c)\)) or we get stuck (when \(\gcd(a,b)>1\)).

2. Algorithm Choice & Rationale  
   - We only need to check reachability, not to output the actual sequence.  
   - If \(\gcd(a,b)\neq1\), no way to arrive at numerator \(1\).  
   - If \(\gcd(a,b)=1\), run the Euclidean algorithm by repeated mod:
       Let \(x=a,y=b\).  
       While \(x>1\):  
         \(r = y \bmod x\);  
         \(y\gets x;\; x\gets r;\)  
       End while.  
       At termination \(x=1\) and \(y\) is the last nonzero remainder.  This \(y\) is exactly the denominator when the numerator first becomes \(1\).  We compare it to \(c\).

3. Complexity Analysis  
   - Each test: one \(\gcd\) plus one small loop of \(\mathcal O(\log\max(a,b))\).  
   - With \(T\le10^3\), overall time \(\mathcal O(T\log N)\) is more than fast enough.  
   - Space is \(\mathcal O(1)\).

4. Edge Cases & Pitfalls  
   - If \(a=1\), we immediately have \(\sqrt{1/b}\).  The loop is skipped and the final \(y=b\) is tested against \(c\).  
   - Ensure integer types are large enough (all values \(\le10^6\), so 64-bit or even 32-bit is safe).  
   - Check \(\gcd\neq1\) first to shortcut.

[Code Implementation]
```cpp
/* 
  Algorithm: Simulate the two‐operation “arc+tan” step 
  which corresponds to one subtraction step in the Euclidean algorithm.
  We succeed iff gcd(a,b)==1 and the final 'y' when 'x' becomes 1 equals c. 
*/
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int T;
    cin >> T;
    while (T--) {
        long long a, b, c;
        cin >> a >> b >> c;

        // If gcd != 1, we can never get numerator = 1 exactly.
        if (gcd(a, b) != 1) {
            cout << "NO\n";
            continue;
        }

        // Run a Euclidean‐mod loop until the smaller becomes 1.
        long long x = a, y = b;
        while (x > 1) {
            long long r = y % x;
            y = x;
            x = r;
        }
        // Now x == 1, and y is the final denominator such that
        // we have transformed to sqrt(1/y).
        if (y == c) 
            cout << "YES\n";
        else 
            cout << "NO\n";
    }
    return 0;
}
```

[Problem Analysis]
1. Problem Essence & Type  
   We are given all but one of the permutations of `{0,1,…,n−1}` (there are `n!` total). Each “account” is a length-`n` string with distinct digits from 0 to `n−1`. Exactly one permutation is missing; we must recover it.  
   Category: Hashing/XOR or Bitwise Tricks (no heavy data structures needed).

2. Algorithm Choice & Rationale  
   Observe that XOR is its own inverse and commutative. If we XOR all digits in each fixed position over all `n!` permutations, then XOR with all input permutations, the result is exactly the missing permutation.  
   - Compute, for each position `j=0…n−1`, `xor_input[j] = XOR of all input account digits at position j`.  
   - Compute `xor_all_perms[j] = XOR of position-j digits across *all* n! permutations`.  
     It can be shown that `xor_all_perms[j]` is zero for `n≥3` (because each digit appears `(n−1)!` times, and `(n−1)!` is even when `n−1≥2`), and for `n=2` it equals `0⊕1=1`.  
   - The missing digit at position `j` is `xor_input[j] ⊕ xor_all_perms[j]`.

3. Complexity Analysis  
   - Time: O(n · (n!)). For n=10, n!≈3.6·10^6, so about 36·10^6 simple XOR ops: fits in ~0.1s.  
   - Space: O(n) auxiliary.

4. Edge Cases & Pitfalls  
   - n=2 is a special parity case; we handle it explicitly.  
   - Leading zeros must be preserved (we treat accounts as strings).  
   - Large input (~3.6M lines) → use fast I/O.

[Code Implementation]
```cpp
/* 
   Find the missing permutation by XORing all input permutations 
   and XORing that with the XOR of all permutations (which is 0 for n>=3, 
   and 0^1=1 for n=2 in each position).
*/
#include <bits/stdc++.h>
using namespace std;

int main(){
    ios::sync_with_stdio(false);
    cin.tie(nullptr);

    int n;
    cin >> n;
    // Determine xor_all_perms: = XOR of {0..n-1} if (n-1)! is odd, else 0.
    // (n-1)! is odd only when n-1 < 2 => n < 3 => n==2
    int xor_all_perms = 0;
    if(n == 2){
        // XOR of digits 0 and 1
        xor_all_perms = 0 ^ 1;
    }

    vector<int> xor_pos(n, 0);
    string s;
    int total = 1;
    // Read n! - 1 lines
    for(int i = 0; i < (int)tgamma(n+1) - 1; i++){
        cin >> s;
        for(int j = 0; j < n; j++){
            xor_pos[j] ^= (s[j] - '0');
        }
    }

    // Recover the missing account
    string missing(n, '0');
    for(int j = 0; j < n; j++){
        int digit = xor_pos[j] ^ xor_all_perms;
        missing[j] = char('0' + digit);
    }

    cout << missing << "\n";
    return 0;
}
```
